The First Minister has come under fire for her handling of SNP MP Patrick Grady, who was found to have committed sexual misconduct. Douglas Ross asks why Mr Grady still has the First Minister's backing. He said: "There was a ruling and a sanction from the independent complaints and grievance system within the UK Parliament, that that sanction doesn't have to be the same adopted by the SNP parliamentary party at Westminster. Pat Grady has served just two days suspension from the SNP at Westminster. Two days is an insult!" The First Minister insists she has already been clear about these issues and stresses that the MP's behaviour was wrong and said she is "very sorry" Mr Grady's victim was subjected to an unwanted sexual advance. READ COVERAGE BELOW...